location: Yuma East Wetlands, Yuma, Arizona, United States
remarks: XC314730 © Bobby Wilcox // Yuma East Wetlands, Yuma, Arizona (32.7257, -114.6074), United States // 40m // 06:00h, 2016-04-30 // call // This call, sometimes referred to as the squeal or squeak duet, is given by two birds who have been foraging apart and get too far apart and then come back together.  It is typically given by a mated pair but can be adult and juveniles or two juveniles as well.  I did not get a good enough look to age these birds but I suspect they were adults.  Recording taken from about 20' away and the birds were on the ground.  The process of finding each other and coming back together may have been initiated in response to my presence as a perceived threat.   /  / bird-seen:yes /  / playback-used:no

Two call types are exhibited: one is a repeated House Sparrow like âcheep" and the other is a flight note of a couple of different types.  /  / This recording was made with an iPhone 5s with the built-in microphone and the RÃ¸de Rec application. This recording has not been modified in any manner. There is some talking by the recordist. /  / Dusky Flycatcher: cheeps 0:01, 0:03, 0:04.5, 0:06, 0:07, 0:09, 0:11, 0:12 (a more distant individual), 0:13.5, 0:14, 0:15.6, 0:17.5 (17.9), 0:22.5 (23.129), 0:23 (several cheeps at 23.1, 24.1, 24.6 (distant), 25.2, 26.3, 27.8 /  / Dusky Flycatcher: flight notes 0:18 a rapid series of doubled chips at 18.3, 18.7, 19.4, followed by a different single chip note at 19.9 and then a doubled chip at 20.85, again followed by single chips at 21.15, and 21.47 /  / Mountain Chickadee: 0:10, 0:15.33 /  / bird-seen:yes /  / playback-used:no // also:  Mountain Chickadee

location: Palo Verde, Imperial County, California, United States
remarks: XC277243 © Jennifer Tobin // Palo Verde, Imperial County, California (33.351, -114.7), United States // 70m // 06:00h, 2015-05-16 // call // Sound amplified.  Habitat a sparse mix of mostly tamarisk and arrowweed with some mesquite and other desert vegetation.  The birds were in short vegetation (less than 2 meters off the ground) within a few meters of me.  This is an interaction between two ATFLs at a territory boundary.  They behaved aggressively towards each other, getting in to some fluttering squabbles.  Both birds were giving this call, but this recording is primarily of one individual.  The vocalizing bird is believed to be a female, as the male was detected nearby giving the territorial "Ka-breer!" call.  She had been carrying food all morning in to a mesquite about 50 meters west from where she is calling.  The nest was in this mesquite and now has at least 4 dependent young.  The agitated manner of the call and the aggressive behavior is the result of a member of a neighboring pair (believed to be the female as well) coming to the territory boundary within 50 meters of her young.  The second pair was observed multiple times carrying food in to a tamarisk about 75 meters SE of the spot this interaction took place. /  / bird-seen:yes /  / playback-used:no

location: Poway, San Diego County, California, United States
remarks: XC330125 © Joshua Jaeger // Poway, San Diego County, California (33.011, -117.0098), United States // 240m // 17:36h, 2016-07-28 // call, song // Ever since I first identified that there were resident Canyon Wrens both at Lake Poway and Blue Sky Ecological Reserve, I have been attempting to obtain visual and auditory proof of their presence, but they sing and call fairly infrequently, and are more cryptic than the other wrens seen in the surrounding areas.  However, on this day I heard and saw one bird on the rock pile near the trail junction merging with Blue Sky Ecological Reserve.  Fortunately, the bird continued to call and sing for several minutes and even made appearances on the rocks.  Although I was finally able to get a recording, I was unable to get a photograph due to its swiftness.  I made a few whistles and hisses to try and keep it out of its den, and although it kept it around longer, this was still not enough to snap a picture.  The most audible calls and singing occur from 0:43 onward. /  / bird-seen:yes /  / playback-used:no // also:  Lesser Goldfinch

location: Laguna Dam Conservation Area, Yuma County, Arizona, United States
remarks: XC315931 © Bobby Wilcox // Laguna Dam Conservation Area, Yuma County, Arizona (32.8331, -114.4721), United States // 50m // 07:30h, 2016-05-10 // male, song // Very strange song from an adult male Common Yellowthroat.  This was a marshy patch of land consisting of cattails and rushes surrounding an 'island' of partially flooded small mesquite trees and arrowweed.   It sounds similar to a type of Wilson's Warbler song but I was drawn to the bird because the Wilson's Warblers that migrate through here do not usually sing this type of song in my experience, so I wasn't sure what it was.  The bird was being very furtive, in the vein of a Common Yellowthroat or MacGillivray's Warbler.  What first got me thinking it was a Common Yellowthroat was when I heard it do a typical COYE call from the same spot as the song was coming.  Being that the song was so weird and MGWA has a similar call I thought perhaps it was just an odd MGWA practicing its song while migrating.  I was doing a survey so I had to abandon the bird but when I came back past the spot later it was still singing from the same place so I began investigating again.  I chased it around for close to an hour, making recordings and trying to get a look at it.  Finally I zeroed in on a spot where it was singing consistently and crept to within ~15ft.  There were no other birds around.  Out from the exact spot where the singing had come from hopped an adult male COYE (albeit a little scruffy looking).  I did not see the song emerge directly from his bill.  But I saw him fly to a clump of brush not 10ft from me and immediately the same song burst forth from that very spot so I am 100% certain of the singing bird's identity.  At this point I continued to observe the bird fly from brush clump to brush clump and sing the weird song and utter typical COYE calls.  In most of the recordings I took it seems to be countersinging with COYEs nearby to some extent which seems to indicate that it knows what its song it 'supposed to' song like.  At no point during my pursuit of this bird did it ever, to my knowledge or listening, switch to the typical COYE song.   /  / *Note: I originally uploaded this recording as having 'seen' the bird but technically at this time I had not actually seen it.  Later uploaded recordings (XC315932 and XC315933) reflect having seen the bird and making a definitive ID.  Based on the static location, similar skulky behavior and the fact that the song was consistent over the entire time period, I am confident that this bird, recorded 2.5 hours earlier, is the same bird that was later seen and appears in XC315932 and XC315933. /  / bird-seen:no /  / playback-used:no // also:  Common Yellowthroat, Yellow-headed Blackbird, Killdeer, American Coot

location: Angeles Crest Highway mile 65.92, San Gabriel Mountains, Los Angeles County, California, United States
remarks: XC143461 © Lance A. M. Benner // Angeles Crest Highway mile 65.92, San Gabriel Mountains, Los Angeles County, California (34.35, -117.8315), United States // 2200m // 23:30h, 2013-07-23 // call // This is a flammulated owl recorded at a range of about 15 meters in an area with white firs, sugar pines, and Jeffrey pines.  The bird was perched in a white fir roughly 10 meters up (slightly less than half way between the ground and the top).  Numerous insects are also audible. /  / Processing: I edited out some of the beginning and end of the file and amplified it by a factor of four. /  / Equipment: Olympus LS-10 equipped with a Sennheiser MKE-400 short shotgun microphone. /  / Conditions: clear sky, full moon (which was well up in the east), winds almost calm, temperature about 17 C. /  / We originally played a flammulated recording for a few minutes, did not hear the bird, so I switched to playing a western screech owl recording.  After a couple of minutes I heard the flammulated owl (we never heard any screech owls).  This is a site where we've heard flammulated owl intermittently in recent years and have documented it on eBird. /  / One or two great horned owls that were calling naturally are audible in the background. /  / bird-seen:no /  / playback-used:yes // also:  Great Horned Owl

location: Three Points, Angeles National Forest, Los Angeles County, California, United States
remarks: XC195626 © Lance A. M. Benner // Three Points, Angeles National Forest, Los Angeles County, California (34.3434, -117.983), United States // 1800m // 21:32h, 2014-09-12 // call // "Wac wac" call in response to playing a northern saw-whet owl recording.  A short time after this recording ended, I started hearing female squawk and male territorial calls from the same direction.  I didn't play any great horned owl vocalizations.  This is an uncommon GHOW vocalization, and to identify it, I compared this recording with one on the "Voices of North American Owls" CD.  I also compared the recording with spotted owl, long-eared owl, and even mule deer (which I saw nearby) recordings and was able to exclude those species.  A faint western screech owl is audible in the background and earlier I had also heard some whines from a northern saw-whet owl. /  / Habitat: Edge of an open forest with Coulter pine, canyon live oak, bigcone Douglas Fir, incense cedar, and chaparral  species. /  / Equipment: Olympus LS-10 with a Telinga 22 inch dish and a Sennheiser ME62 microphone. /  / Modifications to the file: cropped and amplified by 10 dB. /  / bird-seen:no /  / playback-used:yes // also:  Western Screech Owl

location: Dayton, Lyon County, Nevada, United States
remarks: XC253954 © Bobby Wilcox // Dayton, Lyon County, Nevada (39.2012, -119.5613), United States // 1400m // 13:30h, 2015-06-23 // call, female, male // This was a female calling repeatedly from its nest in a 6-7ft high sagebrush about 10ft from me.  There were at least 3 nestlings that were being fed periodically by the male while the female sat on the nest.  I believe this call may have been related to our presence as we had inadvertently set up camp in the midst of a LEGO communal nesting site.  For the most part they were unfazed but if we moved around a lot near a nest and the female was sitting on it she would make this call constantly (repeated high-pitched cheeping).  The male meanwhile, is making a plaintive rather mournful call in the background and waiting until we seemed to not be looking to go in and feed the nestlings.  After a few days of observation it seemed that the male would always make this call immediately prior to coming into the nest to feed and then again just after departing the nest and landing on a nearby branch.  He would then go out again to forage.   /  / bird-seen:yes /  / playback-used:no

location: Buckhorn Campground, San Gabriel Mountains, Los Angeles County, California, United States
remarks: XC329436 © Lance A. M. Benner // Buckhorn Campground, San Gabriel Mountains, Los Angeles County, California (34.346, -117.915), United States // 2000m // 22:25h, 2016-07-20 // begging call, juvenile // Heard in response to playback of flammulated owl calls.   Although we heard this bird vocalize numerous times over several minutes, and from at least two locations, I was able to get only one recording of the sounds.   /  / The ID is based on comparison with numerous other juvenile long-eared owl recordings in my own library and with many in Xeno-Canto.  I also checked dozens of flammulated owl adult and fledgling and great horned owl fledgling recordings.  This call doesn't match any sound I've ever recorded for western screech owl, northern saw-whet owl, northern pygmy owl, or spotted owl.    /  / Equipment: Sony PCM-M10 recorder, Sennheiser ME62 microphone, and a Telinga 22 inch parabolic dish. / Modifications to the file: cropped. /  / bird-seen:no /  / playback-used:yes

location: Lake Hughes Road, Los Angeles County, California, United States
remarks: XC332508 © Lance A. M. Benner // Lake Hughes Road, Los Angeles County, California (34.6071, -118.5608), United States // 600m // 19:18h, 2016-03-26 // call, male // Faint recording of male advertising calls.  Uploaded for documentation because long-eared owl is a rare species in this area.  The sounds are faint and it may be necessary to use headphones or earbuds to hear them.  Recorded 20 minutes after sunset in thick trees along a riparian corridor that had an active creek.   Earlier in the day I hiked into this site and found a nest.  The sounds on this recording are probably a male, based on the low frequency of the hoots.   /  / Continuation of the file that appears in XC332503 and XC3323504.  I split the file into three pieces to crop out two gunshots partway through the original recording.   /  / Equipment: Sony PCM-M10 recorder, Sennheiser ME62 microphone, and a Telinga 22 inch parabola.   / Modifications to the file: cropped and amplified by 10 dB.   /  / Water in the creek and frogs are also audible. /  / Due to the low frequency of the calls, which have a wavelength larger than the diameter of the dish, it probably would have been better to use a shotgun mic. /  / bird-seen:no /  / playback-used:no // also:  Black Phoebe, Nuttall's Woodpecker

Benner // Lake Hughes Road, Los Angeles County, California (34.6071, -118.5608), United States // 600m // 14:41h, 2016-05-14 // call // Faint calls made by an adult long-eared owl in mid afternoon after we accidentally flushed it. It may be necessary to use headphones or earbuds to hear the owl.  We also heard fledgling vocalizations but they stopped before I was able to record them.   /  / The owl calls occur at a frequency of about 700 Hz, last about 0.35 seconds, and appear seven times starting at 0.6, 7.4, 13.0, 17.8, 22.1, 26.6, and 30.8 seconds into the recording. /  / These calls appear to be an uncommon vocalization by this species, which is part of the reason why I'm uploading the recording.  Long-eared owl is also rare in this area so this recording helps document the presence of the species despite the marginal quality of the recording. /  / California quail calls are louder than those of the owl and occur at a higher pitch. /  / Same owl, location, and date as in XC332520. /  / Equipment: Sony PCM-M10 recorder and a Sennheiser MKE-400 microphone. / Modifications to the file: cropped and amplified by 4.4 dB. /  / Sounds of a person walking and the wind are also audible. /  / Recorded at a range of roughly 20-30 meters. /  / bird-seen:yes /  / playback-used:no // also:  California Quail

location: Cloud Burst Summit, San Gabriel Mountains, Los Angeles County, California, United States
remarks: XC143583 © Lance A. M. Benner // Cloud Burst Summit, San Gabriel Mountains, Los Angeles County, California (34.351, -117.934), United States // 2100m // 21:14h, 2011-06-23 // begging call, juvenile // Fledgling northern saw-whet owl calls.  There are at least three birds vocalizing.   We saw two and I photographed one with a point & shoot camera.   /  / The closest bird was about 10 meters from us. The birds were in Jeffrey pines and white firs; there are also sugar pines and incense cedars in the area. We used their sounds to locate the birds (except for the brief sightings); this suggested that the birds were staying within about 5 meters of the ground and generally in thick vegetation where they were hard to see.  The one exception was the bird we photographed that popped out into the open briefly in a Jeffrey pine. /  / Recorded with a Marantz PMD670 digital recorder (*.wav file) equipped with a Sennheiser ME67 shotgun microphone. /  / Modifications to the file: I cropped the beginning and end.   /  /  / bird-seen:yes /  / playback-used:yes

This bird was listed as "rare" for this location.  I had inquired with the eBird reviewer for Orange County and questioned why  its considered rare - he wrote:  "this species is quite rare along the coast in Orange county. If you look at the eBird range map, you can see that there is only one previous record for San Juan Capistrano. You can also see that the large majority of sightings are inland, with relatively few records scattered along the coast (anywhere west of I-5), mostly in the wilderness parks between Newport and Laguna Niguel. location: Old Topanga Canyon Road/Creekside Park entrance road, Santa Monica Mountains, Los Angeles County, California, United States
remarks: XC206514 © Lance A. M. Benner // Old Topanga Canyon Road/Creekside Park entrance road, Santa Monica Mountains, Los Angeles County, California (34.1338, -118.635), United States // 340m // 08:10h, 2014-12-14 // call // Natural calls heard along a small creek that had a little bit of water and abundant, thick, low vegetation along both sides.  Identification based on calls, which both of us have heard elsewhere recently and many times before.  I later played a recording for comparison and found a very good match.  I subsequently checked audio spectrograms of other recordings of the calls for this species and found excellent matches.  I tried playback after we heard the bird calling naturally but then it  stopped vocalizing. From its calls it was clear that it moved rapidly under the vegetation along the creek.  This is typical behavior for this species on its wintering grounds.   The babitat at this location is ideal for this species.  The marker for this species is placed right on top of where I last heard the bird.  This was the first time we've found this species at this location in the 12 years we've conducted the Christmas Bird Count along this road. /  / Recorded with an iPhone 5S using the "Voice Memo" app.  No external microphone. /  / Modifications to the file: cropped and amplified by 10 dB. /  / bird-seen:no /  / playback-used:no // also:  California Thrasher

location: Furnace Creek Ranch, Death Valley National Park, United States
remarks: XC163954 © Chris Howard // Furnace Creek Ranch, Death Valley National Park (36.4605, -116.8682), United States // -60m // 17:00h, 2014-01-04 // call // Chimp chimp. The sun had set and the Death Valley CBC day was done as were dropped off at the Furnace Creek golf course parking lot. We walked over to the little steam west of the parking lot to admire the sunset over the Panamints and reminisce about the good birds we'd had over the years in this little ditch, when we first heard this wren calling chimp - chimp ------ chimp. When we heard the distinctive call note, we knew we had either had a Pacific Wren or a Wilson's Warbler, the latter would be much rarer in January. The bird emerged from under the tangled tamarisk and we saw a little chocolate brown bird with a very short tail, always held at a 45Â° angle. The bird was basically the size and shape of a ping-pong ball. The bird was extensively rusty dark chocolate brown. It liked to scuttle among the low downed branches. We played for it briefly and it got agitated and flew up to eye level perches, giving us definitive views, then flew directly between us a couple times to adjacent trees. It got dark and impossible to see this little dark bird, always hiding in dark tamarisk recesses. We were able to flag down Scott Page and another birder (Dave), who were able to get views of the bird. /  / bird-seen:yes

location: Poway, San Diego County, California, United States
remarks: XC247705 © Joshua Jaeger // Poway, San Diego County, California (33.0059, -117.0136), United States // 280m // 18:30h, 2015-06-01 // call, male // The male Tricolored Blackbird was seen sitting in a low-lying branch of a eucalyptus tree about ten feet off the ground, near the start of the trail around the lake at the boat dock.  There was a family of three sitting on the bench that was under the tree the bird was sitting in, so most of its other vocalizations were drowned out.  The bird was initially mistaken for a male Brewer's Blackbird, until it was noted that its eye was dark, and then it turned its body away from me to reveal the red and white wing patch.  The other blackbirds were not harassing it, although the bird looked agitated, as it made the recorded call at least three times, while at the same time ruffling its feathers while doing it.  It's unknown if this was an alarm call, but the bird did not appear to make the call on a regular interval, and only made the call when the Brewer's Blackbirds were flying near the tree it was perched in. /  / bird-seen:yes /  / playback-used:no

location: Poway, San Diego County, California, United States
remarks: XC331394 © Joshua Jaeger // Poway, San Diego County, California (33.0156, -117.0064), United States // 220m // 12:55h, 2016-08-13 // call // There was at least one Nuthatch seen on the bird-watching trip today.  The one in the recording was first seen near the trail junction between Blue Sky and Lake Poway, and it proceeded down the trail at roughly the same pace as me, then began foraging in the eucalyptus tree at the end of the trail where it leads out of the forest and towards Lake Ramona.  It's possible there were two individuals on the trail because I thought I could vaguely hear another one calling off in the distance towards Lake Poway, but I was not certain.  The individual in this recording may very well be the same one I had been repeatedly seeing for the past couple weeks at Lake Poway.  Normally that bird is seen at Lake Poway in the evening, then by sundown, flies towards Blue Sky. /  / bird-seen:yes /  / playback-used:no // also:  Acorn Woodpecker

location: Guerneville, Sonoma County, California, United States
remarks: XC418656 Â© Teresa and Miles Tuffli // Guerneville, Sonoma County, California (38.4914, -123.0191), United States // 110m // 10:30h, 2018-06-04 // begging call, juvenile // Hi there, I got a pretty poor look at a very young fledgling (through a lot of bramble) that I believe was making the high pitched calls heard at the beginning of this recording. There were a couple Wilson's Warblers active in the same area and I did see one fly over to the general bramble area where the fledgling was sitting. Unfortunately, I didn't actually see them interact and I am unsure if I actually saw a very young WIWA or a different bird. The bird was pretty plain gray, with big black eyes and a large mouth gape.  /  / Does anybody know if these vocalizations are from a begging Wilson's Warbler fledgling? I could only find one recording of a fledgling WIWA in the database by Ian Cruickshank and I was unsure which vocalization he was referring to as the fledgling calls. /  / Any help is appreciated. Thanks! /  / Highpass filter @ 12khz / Redwood/Doug-fir forest /  / Miles /  / bird-seen:yes /  / playback-used:no // also:  Spotted Towhee, Wilson's Warbler, Dark-eyed Junco, Brown Creeper
